Here's a clean approach using merged `ResourceDictionary` swapping:

**1. Define each theme as a separate ResourceDictionary:**

```xml
<!-- Themes/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
                    x:Class="MyApp.Themes.LightTheme">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="Accent">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

Create matching `DarkTheme.xaml` and `HighContrastTheme.xaml` with different color values.

**2. Create a theme service:**

```csharp
public enum AppTheme { Light, Dark, HighContrast }

public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;

        // Remove existing theme dictionary (always the last one added)
        mergedDicts.Clear();

        ResourceDictionary newTheme = theme switch
        {
            AppTheme.Dark => new Themes.DarkTheme(),
            AppTheme.HighContrast => new Themes.HighContrastTheme(),
            _ => new Themes.LightTheme()
        };

        mergedDicts.Add(newTheme);

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("AppTheme", theme.ToString());
    }

    public static void LoadSavedTheme()
    {
        var saved = Preferences.Get("AppTheme", nameof(AppTheme.Light));
        if (Enum.TryParse<AppTheme>(saved, out var theme))
            ApplyTheme(theme);
    }
}
```

**3. Apply the saved theme at startup in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ThemeService.LoadSavedTheme();
}
```

**4. Use `DynamicResource` (not `StaticResource`) in your XAML so changes propagate immediately:**

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label TextColor="{DynamicResource TextPrimary}" Text="Hello" />
</ContentPage>
```

**5. Wire up the settings page:**

```xml
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker" SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged">
    <Picker.ItemsSource>
        <x:Array Type="{x:Type x:String}">
            <x:String>Light</x:String>
            <x:String>Dark</x:String>
            <x:String>High Contrast</x:String>
        </x:Array>
    </Picker.ItemsSource>
</Picker>
```

```csharp
void OnThemeChanged(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    var theme = ThemePicker.SelectedIndex switch
    {
        1 => AppTheme.Dark,
        2 => AppTheme.HighContrast,
        _ => AppTheme.Light
    };
    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(theme);
}
```

**Key points:**
- `DynamicResource` is essential — it re-evaluates when the dictionary changes.
- Keep the same `x:Key` names across all three theme files so bindings resolve correctly.
- `Preferences` persists the choice across app restarts.
